  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>Trello Review</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · 10 min read</div>
      <div class="author">By <a href={`/authors/${authorSlug}`}>{author}</a></div>

      <Image src={heroImg} alt="Trello Kanban board project management interface on a laptop screen" width={1200} height={600} loading="eager" fetchpriority="high" class="hero-img" />

      <ProductCTACard
        productName={productName}
        brand={brand}
        rating={ratingValue}
        price={bestPrice}
        slug={productSlug}
        editorChoice={false}
      />

      <ReviewMeta
        authorSlug={authorSlug}
        lastUpdated={lastUpdated}
        testingDuration={testingDuration}
        productsTested={productsTested}
      />

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★☆</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily use across a marketing team</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> <strong>Trello</strong> is the simplest and fastest Kanban board you can use in 2026. The free plan supports up to 10 boards with unlimited cards, Butler automation is included at no cost, and the 200+ Power-Ups cover most integrations. It lacks Gantt charts, native time tracking, and struggles at 500+ cards per board — but for small teams who want a visual board they can learn in 30 minutes, Trello is the best free option available.
      </div>

      <p>Trello launched in 2011 and popularized the Kanban board for non-engineering teams. Acquired by Atlassian in 2017, Trello now sits alongside Jira and Confluence in the Atlassian suite, positioning itself as the lightweight visual alternative to Jira's complexity. We tested Trello for 60 days across a 6-person marketing team running content calendars, campaign pipelines, and cross-team operations, to see whether the free plan and Butler automation hold up against Asana, Monday, and Linear.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against Asana and Monday, see our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> breakdown. If you want a software-team issue tracker, the <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a> covers the fastest option on the market.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Kanban Boards: Fast, Visual, and Simple</h3>
      <p>Trello is Kanban-first. Every project is a board, every board has columns (lists), and every list has cards. You drag cards between lists to move work forward — To Do, Doing, Done is the canonical setup, but you can name lists anything. The interface is clean, colorful, and instantly understandable; a new team member can learn the basics in under 30 minutes, which is Trello's single biggest advantage over Asana and Monday.</p>

      <p>The board is fast. Dragging a card, reordering lists, and editing card details all happen in under 100ms with no lag, even on boards with 100+ cards. Trello's performance is the best of any Kanban tool we have tested — Linear is comparable for engineering workflows, but Trello is faster for non-technical project management. The cards support checklists, due dates, labels, attachments, comments, and custom fields (Premium only), which covers 90% of what a small team needs.</p>

      <p>The limitation is scale. Trello struggles on boards with 500+ cards — search slows down, the board takes longer to load, and scrolling becomes laggy. We hit this limit on a legacy content calendar with 620 cards accumulated over 18 months. Trello's recommendation is to archive old cards, which works but feels like a workaround. If your team generates 500+ active cards per board, you need a tool built for scale — Asana and Monday handle large projects better.</p>

      <h3>Butler Automation: No-Code Workflows Included Free</h3>
      <p>Butler is Trello's no-code automation builder, and it is included on every plan — including Free. Butler lets you create rules (when a card is moved to Done, mark all checklists complete and remove the due date), scheduled actions (every Monday at 9am, create a card in the To Do list), and card buttons (click a button on a card to add a standard checklist and assign a due date). The Free plan includes 1,000 Butler commands per month per workspace, which is enough for most small teams.</p>

      <p>In our testing, Butler replaced Zapier for every workflow we needed. We set up a rule that auto-assigned a team member when a card was labeled "Design", a scheduled action that created a weekly review card every Friday, and a card button that added a content checklist with one click. All three worked reliably for 60 days with no missed triggers. The command limit of 1,000 per month is generous — we used about 300 commands in our busiest month.</p>

      <p>The catch is that Butler is limited to Trello-internal actions. You cannot trigger an action in Slack or Google Drive directly from Butler — you need a Power-Up or Zapier for cross-tool automation. For most small teams, Butler handles 80% of automation needs without a third-party tool, which is a real cost saving.</p>

      <h3>Power-Ups: 200+ Integrations, But Limited on Free</h3>
      <p>Power-Ups are Trello's integration system — there are over 200 available, including Slack, Google Drive, Calendar, Jira, GitHub, Dropbox, and Mailchimp. A Power-Up adds a tab to each card (for example, the Slack Power-Up shows the Slack messages related to a card) and can add buttons, automation triggers, and board-level features. The selection is broad and covers most tools a marketing or operations team would use.</p>

      <p>The limitation is the Free plan. Free users can add one Power-Up per board — so if you want Slack and Google Drive on the same board, you must upgrade to Standard ($5 per seat per month) for unlimited Power-Ups. For a 6-person team, that is $30 per month to unlock integrations, which is reasonable but not free. We recommend starting on Free, identifying which Power-Ups you actually use, and upgrading only if you need more than one per board.</p>

      <p>The Atlassian integration is a standout. If your engineering team uses Jira, the Jira Power-Up syncs Trello cards to Jira issues — create a Trello card, and it appears as a Jira issue automatically. We did not test this in depth (our team is non-technical), but Atlassian reports it as one of the most-used Power-Ups, and it makes Trello a genuine lightweight front-end for Jira. See our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison for the engineering-tool breakdown.</p>

      <h3>Mobile Apps: Full Board Editing, Not Read-Only</h3>
      <p>Trello's mobile apps (iOS and Android) are genuinely good — not the stripped-down read-only views that many project tools ship. You can create cards, drag them between lists, add checklists and due dates, comment, and attach photos from your phone. The drag-and-drop works well with touch, and the app is fast on both iOS and Android. We managed the board from phones during a 3-day offsite without opening a laptop.</p>

      <p>The mobile apps support push notifications for card assignments, due dates, and mentions, which kept the team in sync during the offsite. The one limitation is that Butler rules and Power-Up settings are not editable in the mobile app — you need the desktop web app for automation and integration configuration. This is a minor complaint; most teams configure automation once and rarely touch it.</p>

      <h3>Views and Reporting: Kanban-Only Without Premium</h3>
      <p>Trello is Kanban-only on the Free and Standard plans. The Premium plan ($10 per seat per month) adds a Dashboard view (charts of cards by list, label, and due date) and a Timeline view (a horizontal calendar of cards by due date). These views are useful for reporting and planning, but they are not Gantt charts — there is no dependency tracking, no critical path, and no resource allocation. If you need real Gantt charts, you need a third-party Power-Up like BigPicture or a different tool entirely.</p>

      <p>The Dashboard view is basic but functional. It shows card counts by list, by label, and by due date, plus a chart of cards created vs completed over time. For a small team's weekly review, it is enough. For enterprise reporting, it is not — Asana and Monday have significantly better built-in reporting. We used the Dashboard view for our weekly standup, and it covered what we needed, but we exported data to Google Sheets for anything more detailed.</p>

      <p>The lack of native time tracking is a real gap for teams who bill clients. Trello has no built-in timer, and the third-party Power-Ups (Toggl, Harvest, Clockify) add a timer to each card but sync data to their own dashboards, not Trello. If time tracking is core to your workflow, Asana and Monday both have better native options, or you pair Trello with a dedicated tool like Toggl.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>Trello competes against Asana, Monday, and Linear. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tool</th>
            <th>Free Plan</th>
            <th>Views</th>
            <th>Automation</th>
            <th>Best For</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Trello</strong></td>
            <td>10 boards, 1 Power-Up</td>
            <td>Kanban (+ Timeline on Premium)</td>
            <td>Butler (1,000/mo free)</td>
            <td>Small, visual teams</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Asana</td>
            <td>15 users, limited</td>
            <td>List, Kanban, Timeline, Calendar</td>
            <td>Rules (paid only)</td>
            <td>Complex projects</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Monday</td>
            <td>2 users, 3 boards</td>
            <td>Table, Kanban, Timeline, Map</td>
            <td>Automations (paid only)</td>
            <td>Visual dashboards</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Linear</td>
            <td>1 user only</td>
            <td>Kanban, List, Roadmap</td>
            <td>None native</td>
            <td>Software teams</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Asana</strong> (free for up to 15 users) offers List, Kanban, Timeline, and Calendar views in one tool, plus a Portfolio view for managing multiple projects. It is more feature-rich than Trello but slower to learn (1 to 2 hours for a new user) and the free plan lacks automation. If your projects need multiple views and dependencies, Asana is the pick — see our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> comparison for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p><strong>Monday</strong> ($0 for 2 users, 3 boards) is the most visual of the three, with a colorful table-based interface and strong dashboard reporting. The free plan is very limited (2 users, 3 boards), and automation requires a paid plan. Monday is best for teams who want visual dashboards and a spreadsheet-like interface. See our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> comparison for details.</p>

      <p><strong>Linear</strong> (free for 1 user, $8 per seat for teams) is the fastest issue tracker for software teams. It is not a direct Trello competitor — Linear is built for engineering workflows with sprints, backlogs, and GitHub integration. If you are a software team, use Linear; if you are a non-technical team, use Trello. See our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Start on the Free plan. Trello Free supports up to 10 boards with unlimited cards and one Power-Up per board, which is enough for a solo user or a small team of 2 to 5 people. Butler automation is included free with 1,000 commands per month. Most teams can run on Free indefinitely — we did for the full 60 days without hitting a limit.</p>

      <p>Upgrade to Standard ($5 per seat per month) if you need more than 10 boards or more than one Power-Up per board. Standard also removes the 10-board limit and adds unlimited Power-Ups, which is the main reason to upgrade. For a 6-person team, Standard costs $30 per month — reasonable for the integrations it unlocks.</p>

      <p>Upgrade to Premium ($10 per seat per month) only if you need the Dashboard and Timeline views. Premium adds these two views plus custom fields, but the views are basic — not a replacement for Asana or Monday's reporting. If reporting is core to your workflow, switch to Asana or Monday instead of paying for Trello Premium.</p>

      <p>Skip Trello and use Asana if your projects need multiple views (List, Timeline, Calendar) and dependencies. Asana is harder to learn but more powerful for complex projects. See our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> comparison for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>Skip Trello and use Linear if you are a software team. Linear has sprints, backlogs, GitHub integration, and a keyboard-first UI that is built for engineering workflows. Trello can fake sprints with columns, but it is not built for it. See our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a> for the full breakdown. Pair Trello with a <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-confluence/">documentation tool</a> for a complete non-technical workflow.</p>

